   </teiHeader>
   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Geneve_1811-02-24_page01.jpg"/>
            <opener>
               <dateline>
                  <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Edgeworthstown_IE">Edgeworth Town</placeName>
                  <date when="1811-02-24">Feb<hi rend="superscript">y</hi>. 24<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>. 1811</date></dateline>
            </opener>
            <p>
               Our friend <persName ref="./Personography.xml#ChenR1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Chenevix</persName> has just written to me and<lb/>
               is anxious for immediate intelligence of the<lb/>
               health of his sister and her family, but <add>he</add> has omitted<lb/>
               to tell me where to direct my answer. He tells<lb/>
               me however that you have called upon him <choice><orig>there-<lb/>fore</orig><reg>therefore</reg></choice>
               you know where he is, and I take the <choice><orig>liber<lb/>ty</orig><reg>liberty</reg></choice>
               of troubling you to convey the enclosed note<lb/>
               to him.<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               It seems a great while since we had the luxury<lb/>
               of a letter from you my dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#DumoE1">Sir</persName> - I know your<lb/>
               head must now be full of politics and regency<lb/>
               &amp;c but I wish you could find a happy moment<lb/>
               for literature and friendship - better things - at<lb/>
               least we who are only lookers-on, in retirement<lb/>
               think so - Pray when you have a moment's <choice><orig>lei-<lb/>sure</orig><reg>leisure</reg></choice>
               write and let me have the pleasure of <choice><orig>greet-<lb/>ing</orig><reg>greeting</reg></choice>
               my <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeR1">father</persName> when he returns home, with a<lb/>
               letter from his good friend <persName ref="./Personography.xml#DumoE1">M. Dumont</persName>. He is now<lb/>
               in <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Dublin_IE">Dublin</placeName> attending the Board of Education - of<lb/>
               the proceedings of which we will send you an<lb/>
               account when anything worthy of your attention<lb/>
               has been done -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               I see <persName ref="./Personography.xml#DumoE1">you</persName> and <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BentJ1">Bentham</persName> mentioned <hi rend="underline">as you ought</hi><lb/>
               and as <hi rend="underline">you ought not to be mentioned</hi> in the last<lb/>
               <note place="top">44</note>
               
               <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Geneve_1811-02-24_page02.jpg"/>  
               Review - of the new code of <add>French</add> laws - Whilst they bow to<lb/>
               superiority these critics cannot refrain, even at that moment<lb/>
               from giving a cut and a taunt - No matter if public<lb/>
               attention to be thus directed from time to time to that<lb/>
               book it will rise to its just height in the opinion of all<lb/>
               those who can judge - The author might say like the beauty<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               "Let me be seen! Could I that wish obtain<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               "All other wishes my own power would gain" -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               Pray tell me what you think of <persName ref="./Personography.xml#KirwR1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Kirwan's</persName> <title ref="./Workography.xml#Essay4"><hi rend="underline">Essay on</hi><lb/>
               <hi rend="underline">happiness</hi></title>, which we sent you, and of the pamphlet<lb/>
               <hi rend="underline">On the policy of sending troops abroad</hi>, which <persName ref="./Personography.xml#ChenR1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Che-<lb/>nevix</persName>
               brought you - You will find <persName ref="./Personography.xml#ChenR1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Chenevix</persName><lb/>
               conversation, I think, peculiarly entertaining &amp;<lb/>
               interesting to you, from his having lived so much<lb/>
               on the Continent &amp; from his having lately returned<lb/>
               with such a vast <del>&amp; various</del> assortment of anecdotes<lb/>
               French, Spanish, and German of living &amp; distinguished<lb/>
               characters - I could wish however, that his assortment<lb/>
               had, even for variety's sake some few anecdotes of good<lb/>
               as well as bad people - for <add>hearing of</add> - vice - vice - vice crimes<lb/>
               crimes - crimes fatigues and depresses the mind<lb/>
               - It is a monotony which is as bad for taste as for morals<lb/>
               - both indignation &amp; attention are worn out for want<lb/>
               of the relief of contrast - I hope as he acknowledges that<lb/>
               there are good people in <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#ENK">England</placeName> that he will lay in<lb/>
               a store of <hi rend="underline">good</hi> anecdotes for the honor of poor human<lb/>
               nature and for the credit of his own taste -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               Do tell me if you have heard lately <hi rend="underline">from</hi><lb/>
               or <hi rend="underline">of</hi> any of our friends in <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Paris_FR">Paris</placeName> - <persName ref="./Personography.xml#GautX1">Madame Gautier</persName><lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#PastA1">Madame Pastoret</persName> - <persName ref="./Personography.xml#PictM1">Pictet</persName> or that poor <persName ref="./Personography.xml#LavoM1">Comtesse <choice><orig>Rum-<lb/>
               
                  <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_Geneve_1811-02-24_page03.jpg"/>
               ford</orig><reg>Rumford</reg></choice></persName> - Has she beaten at last - or is she beaten? has she bought<lb/>
               her separation from her philosophic tyrant? - or is she<lb/>
               still bargaining for her liberty -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               I have lately heard from <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Edinburgh_STK">Edinburgh</placeName> a high<lb/>
               character of a <persName ref="./Personography.xml#SimoL1">M. Simonde</persName> &amp; his <persName ref="./Personography.xml#SimoF1">wife</persName> and <persName ref="./Personography.xml#SimoX1">sister</persName>, travellers<lb/>
               who have lately returned from <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#US">America</placeName>, - originally<lb/>
               French or Swiss - with all the amiable parts as I am<lb/>
               told of the French character free from its common <choice><orig>de-<lb/>fects</orig><reg>defects</reg></choice>
               - Do you know anything of them - and have they<lb/>
               any thing to say to <hi rend="underline"><persName ref="./Personography.xml#SismJ1">Simonde</persName> sur <title ref="./Workography.xml#Riche1">la Richesse <choice><orig>commer-<lb/>-ciale</orig><reg>commerciale</reg></choice></title></hi>
               which we have just got from your <choice><orig>recommen-<lb/>-dation -</orig><reg>recommendation</reg></choice>
            </p>
            <p>
               I hear that <persName ref="./Personography.xml#ScotW1">Scott</persName> is now at work upon a new <title ref="./Workography.xml#Lordo1" cert="medium">poem</title><lb/>
               - in which I am told <add>by some</add> that Scotch &amp; Irish history or legends<lb/>
               are to be blended - by others I am told that the Pretend<lb/>
               history is to be the groundwork of the fable - At all counts<lb/>
               I hope it will be free from the <hi rend="underline">papillotage</hi> with which<lb/>
               you so justly reproach the <title ref="./Workography.xml#Ladyo1">Lady of the lake</title> - How much<lb/>
               excellent criticism <persName ref="./Personography.xml#ScotW1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Scott</persName> has called forth &amp; of how much<lb/>
               service his popular poems are to the public <del><unclear/> <unclear>la</unclear></del> even<lb/>
               in this point of view - I wish for his own sake, that he<lb/>
               <del>had</del> could read your last letter to my <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeR1">father</persName> before he<lb/>
               finishes his new poem -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               We hear with joy that <persName ref="./Personography.xml#StewD1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Dugald Stewart</persName> has <choice><orig>recover-<lb/>ed</orig><reg>recovered</reg></choice>
               his health and spirits and that he &amp; <persName ref="./Personography.xml#StewH1">M<hi rend="superscirpt">rs</hi>. Stewart</persName><lb/>
               have lately mixed again for a few days at a time,<lb/>
               in the Society of their friends at <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Edinburgh_STK">Edinburgh</placeName> - I entirely<lb/>
               agree with you in thinking that the essays on taste, the<lb/>
               concluding essays of his last work are far preferable to<lb/>
               the first part - Certainly those first essays are on subjects<lb/>
               where as you say - <hi rend="underline">on ne trouvera jamais le dernier</hi><lb/>
               <hi rend="underline">mot</hi> - but can you tell me why people are so apt to grow<lb/>
               
               <note place="top">44</note>
               
               <pb n="4" facs="Edgeworth_Geneve_1811-02-24_page04.jpg"/>
               angry on metaphysical subjects - Why to doubt <add>on subjects where demonstration cannot be had</add> is so often<lb/>
               <add><choice><orig>accounted</orig><reg>unaccounted</reg></choice></add> criminal - And what are all those terrible dangers <add>with</add> which<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#StewD1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Stewart</persName> alarms himself and his readers. - I wish the world<lb/>
               had no other dangers to fear but those which <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HartD1">Hartley's</persName> <choice><orig>vi-<lb/>-bratiuncles</orig><reg>vibratiuncles</reg></choice>
               -or <persName ref="./Personography.xml#TookJ1">Tooke's</persName> etymologies might produce -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               I stop short - for I am ashamed to find myself<lb/>
               writing common place trash to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#DumoE1">M. Dumont</persName>.<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               Let me however thank him, - and not<lb/>
               with common place thanks, for his kindness to my <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeC1">brother</persName><lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeC1">Sneyd</persName> - He and all his <persName ref="./Personography.xml#Edgew2">family</persName> are fully &amp; gratefully<lb/>
               sensible of your goodness to him - and <hi rend="underline">I</hi> am in <choice><orig>particu-<lb/>larly</orig><reg>particularly</reg></choice>
               highly gratified by the interest with which he<lb/>
               has inspired you &amp; the - something approaching to<lb/>
               affection, which you express for him - In a few days<lb/>
               he will come to us from <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Dublin_IE">Dublin</placeName> &amp; begin his first <choice><orig>cir-<lb/>cuit</orig><reg>circuit</reg></choice>
               - well armed with patience &amp; resolved to <choice><orig>perse-<lb/>-vere</orig><reg>persevere</reg></choice>,
               - &amp; to bear being <hi rend="underline">nobody</hi> till he has opportunity<lb/>
               to prove that he is <hi rend="underline">somebody</hi>.<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               Pray if you have not yet seen <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HardF1">Hardy's</persName><lb/>
               <title ref="./Workography.xml#Memoi15">life of Lord Charlemont</title> look at it whenever it falls in<lb/>
               you way - It is a spirited, entertaining &amp; well written<lb/>
               piece of biography - mixed with interesting parts of<lb/>
               modern Irish political history &amp; characters -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               Adieu my dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#DumoE1">Sir</persName> - believe me neither<lb/>
               I nor any one in this family have the least fear<lb/>
               of revenans - when they are friends like you -<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Maria Edgeworth</persName><lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               <pb n="5" facs="Edgeworth_Geneve_1811-02-24_page05.jpg"/>
               I live in hopes - unreasonable hopes<lb/>
               I own - of hearing from you again &amp; receiving<lb/>
               more riches for <title ref="./Workography.xml#Proff1">Prof Ed.</title><lb/>
               Your obliged friend-<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeR1">Rich<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>. Lovell Edgeworth</persName><lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               Several years ago when I saw <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Lord-Mansfields-Monument_ENK">Lord<lb/> Mansfield's monument</placeName><lb/>
               in <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Westminster-Abbey_ENK">Westmin-<lb/>ster Abbey</placeName><lb/>
               where his <persName ref="./Personography.xml#MansW1">Lordship</persName> is <choice><orig>repre-<lb/>sented</orig><reg>represented</reg></choice>
               holding a Roman steelyard, I <damage><unclear>iw</unclear><gap></gap></damage><lb/>
               or rather spoke the following epitaph<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               "High o'er our Courts see sculptured Justice stand"<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               "Poising an even balance in her hand -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               "But <persName ref="./Personography.xml#MansW1">Mansfield</persName> scorning English law at home<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               "The shifting steelyard brought from tyrant <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Rome_IT">Rome</placeName><lb/>
           
               <note place="top">45</note>
            </p>
            <p>
               <pb n="6" facs="Edgeworth_Geneve_1811-02-24_page06.jpg"/>
               <hi rend="underline">Postscript</hi><lb/>
               Just as I finished this long letter I find<lb/>
               that I have been appointed by the <persName ref="./Personography.xml#RichC1">Lord<lb/> Lieutenant</persName><lb/>
               of <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#IE">Ireland</placeName> one of the <choice><orig>Commis-<lb/>-sioners</orig><reg>Commissioners</reg></choice>
               to enquire into the funds for the<lb/>
               education of the people. That prodigious<lb/>
               frauds have been committed, by the<lb/>
               persons who hold these funds, I am<lb/>
               certain, as I had occasion, when I, some<lb/>
               years ago, brought a bill into parliament<lb/>
               for the education of the people, to collect<lb/>
               information upon this subject. You may<lb/>
               judge of the amount of the embezzlements<lb/>
               when I tell you that within these few<lb/>
               <del>years</del> days £1500 a year of which I had<lb/>
               never before heard are embezzled in a <choice><orig>sin-<lb/>-gle</orig><reg>single</reg></choice>
               parish; funds therefore will not be<lb/>
               wanting; but to apply them <choice><orig>advantageous-<lb/>-ly</orig><reg>advantageously</reg></choice>
               will be difficult. Religious, and party<lb/>
               prejudices are not only strong, but they<lb/>
               cross each other in a thousand unforeseen<lb/>
               directions. As the commissioners are to<lb/>
               act without fee or reward, and as many<lb/>
               expensive duties will be enjoined them,<lb/>
               such as employing surveyors to visit <choice><orig>es-<lb/>
               
               <note place="top">46</note>
               
                  <pb n="7" facs="Edgeworth_Geneve_1811-02-24_page07.jpg"/>
               tates</orig><reg>estates</reg></choice> in remote parts of the country I fear that<lb/>
               few men properly qualified will act <choice><orig>ef-<lb/>-fectively</orig><reg>effectively</reg></choice>.
               I will however do all in my<lb/>
               power for a short time. I believe that before<lb/>
               the sitting of parliament the necessary <choice><orig>in-<lb/>-formation</orig><reg>information</reg></choice>
               can be obtained; but if any<lb/>
               thing more is intended than catching hold<lb/>
               of the funds a very different system must<lb/>
               be pursued. Enthusiasts might be found<lb/>
               who to accomplish some favorite theory<lb/>
               might sacrifice their health, or leisure;<lb/>
               interested or corrupt men might likewise<lb/>
               be found, who would be ready to accept<lb/>
               the administration of large sums; but a<lb/>
               business of this sort must not be committed<lb/>
               to enthusiasm or peculation. What I<lb/>
               most fear is that the meaning of the word<lb/>
               education may be confined to the art of<lb/>
               teaching children how to write &amp; read.<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               I hope that I have in some degree a claim<lb/>
               upon your public feelings for whatever<lb/>
               hints may occur to you on this important<lb/>
               subject. I know well that the opposition<lb/>
               sedulously give out that ministers have<lb/>
               entered upon this subject merely par<lb/>
               <hi rend="unnderline">maniere d'acquit</hi> - That they mean only<lb/>
               
               <pb n="8" facs="Edgeworth_Geneve_1811-02-24_page08.jpg"/>
               to get back their pledge without redeeming<lb/>
               it - this I do not believe.<lb/>
            </p>
              <note place="top">47</note>
               
            <pb n="9" facs="Edgeworth_Geneve_1811-02-24_page09.jpg"/>
            <closer>
               To<lb/>
               <address>
               <addrLine/><persName ref="./Personography.xml#DumoE1">S. Dumont Esq<hi rend="superscript">re</hi>.</persName><lb/>
               </address>
            </closer>
         </div>
      </body>
      <back> </back>
   </text>
</TEI>